e's own moment onto other times and cultures, the essays in this collection use the Victorian era as a means of developing a theory and critique of historical reclamation.In Knowing the Past, a distinguished group of Victorian scholars reflect on the Victorian past and examine the Victorians' own sophisticated contributions to debates about historical and cultural knowledge. Confronting, confirming, and opposing the skeptics, the essays provide close readings of particular texts. They encompass the larger constellation of ideas and questions that went into the making of the texts while participating in larger theoretical debates about knowledge of the past and other cultures.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aEnglish literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aHermeneuticsxHistoryy19th century. 0aKnowledge, Theory ofxHistoryy19th century. 0aKnowledge, Theory of, in literature. 4aEngland. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh1 aAnger, Suzy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAnger, Suzy, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBeer, Gillian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBodenheimer, Rosemarie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHerbert, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJoseph, Gerhard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLevine, George, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLoesberg, Jonathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPoovey, Mary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRobbins, Bruce, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/re